# Training Principles

## Purpose

This document defines the annual training methodology for a 12-block year.
It explains:

1. What outcomes we are pursuing
2. How each block contributes to those outcomes
3. What tradeoffs are accepted in each phase
4. How progression is measured and adjusted

## Annual Outcomes

Primary outcomes for the year:

1. Dunk a basketball
2. Achieve side split capability
3. Reach and sustain lean body composition (~10-12% body fat target zone)
4. Maintain and improve D1-level strength standards
5. Reach Clean and Jerk 100 kg

## Methodology

### 1) Two-Block Wave System

Each quality is trained in 2-block waves (8 weeks total):

1. Block A (Accumulation): build volume, skill quality, and tissue tolerance
2. Block B (Intensification/Conversion): increase specificity, speed, or load toward outcome

Reason: one 4-week block is often enough to start adaptation, but not enough to express it reliably.

### 2) Explicit Focus + Tradeoff

Each block has one primary adaptation and one known tradeoff.
This prevents trying to peak all qualities at once.

### 3) Concurrent, Not Equal

All qualities are trained year-round, but not equally:

1. Primary quality gets the most resources
2. Secondary quality is progressed slowly
3. Other qualities are maintained with minimum effective dose

### 4) Fixed Weekly Structure

The weekly template remains stable to reduce complexity and improve consistency:

1. Lower A (Olympic + squat focus + split work)
2. Upper A (press/pull + short mobility)
3. Lower B (jump primer + hinge/front squat + split work)
4. Upper B (press/pull + short mobility)
5. Basketball/Jump day (sprints, approach jumps, dunk attempts)

### 5) Minimum Effective Doses

Non-negotiable weekly doses:

1. Jump/dunk exposure: at least 2 quality exposures (Lower B + Basketball day)
2. Olympic exposure: at least 3 exposures (small/medium/large across lift days)
3. Side-split work: 5-6 exposures per week (2 longer, 3-4 short)
4. Strength exposure: both lower days include squat or hinge loading

## 12-Block Annual Map

| Block | Month | Block Name | 1-liner | Metric | Tradeoff |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Mar '26 | Foundation Cut + Mobility | Build consistency, start leaning out, lock in split work frequency. | 7-day avg BW down 1-2 lb and side-split hip-to-floor -2 cm from baseline. | No max-strength PR testing. |
| 2 | Apr '26 | Strength Base I | Rebuild squat/hinge/chin volume while keeping body comp moving. | Back squat e1RM >=390 lb. | Jump volume capped. |
| 3 | May '26 | Strength Base II | Push max-force outputs and front squat strength. | Front squat top single >=140 kg. | Less upper-body accessory volume. |
| 4 | Jun '26 | Olympic Build I | Improve clean & jerk technique under moderate-heavy load. | Clean & Jerk top single >=80 kg (clean reps). | Deadlift volume reduced. |
| 5 | Jul '26 | Power Conversion I | Convert new strength into speed and jump output. | Approach touch +2 in vs March baseline. | Lower-body hypertrophy reduced. |
| 6 | Aug '26 | Power Conversion II | Increase reactive power and dunk transfer. | Approach touch +4 in vs March baseline. | Squat volume/intensity pulled back slightly. |
| 7 | Sep '26 | Dunk Specific I | Bias basketball takeoff skill and dunk attempts. | Basketball dunk makes >=1/20 attempts. | Olympic volume at maintenance only. |
| 8 | Oct '26 | Dunk Specific II (Peak) | Peak dunk expression with fresh legs. | Basketball dunk makes >=3/20 attempts. | Minimal strength progression focus. |
| 9 | Nov '26 | Mini-Cut + Mobility Peak I | Drive toward lean target while increasing split depth. | Body fat 11-12% (or waist -2.5 in vs March). | Heavy PR attempts paused. |
| 10 | Dec '26 | Olympic Peak I | Rebuild heavy C&J expression after dunk peak. | Clean & Jerk >=90 kg. | Jump work reduced to 1 quality day. |
| 11 | Jan '27 | Olympic Peak II + D1 Realization | Take run at C&J goal and strongest D1-aligned numbers. | Clean & Jerk 95-100 kg and back squat e1RM >=405 lb. | Accessories minimal, fatigue tightly managed. |
| 12 | Feb '27 | Consolidate + Test | Hold lean/performance and test full goal stack. | Side split hip-to-floor <=2 cm and dunk make rate >=3/20 sustained. | Lower training novelty/high-volume work. |

## Progression Rules

### 1) Load Progression

For primary lifts:

1. Add load when all target reps are hit at target effort and technical standard
2. If technical quality drops, keep load and improve execution
3. If two sessions miss target, reduce load 5-8% and rebuild

### 2) Jump Progression

1. Increase jump complexity only when quality is maintained
2. Keep full rest on maximal sprint/jump sets
3. Track makes and touch height weekly; do not chase fatigue

### 3) Flexibility Progression

1. Increase end-range duration or intensity gradually
2. Keep side-split work frequent, low-friction, and scheduled
3. Track objective depth (hip-to-floor) weekly

### 4) Body Composition Progression

1. Rate of loss target: 0.5-1.0 lb/week during cut-focused blocks
2. If performance drops sharply for 2 weeks, reduce deficit and restore recovery
3. Use 7-day average bodyweight, not daily fluctuations

## Scoreboard (Weekly)

Track these every week:

1. Back squat e1RM
2. Clean & Jerk top single
3. Approach touch height
4. Dunk makes out of 20 attempts
5. Side-split hip-to-floor distance
6. 7-day average bodyweight
7. Waist measurement (optional, recommended during cut blocks)

## Decision Rules

Use these simple rules:

1. If primary metric improves: continue plan
2. If primary metric stalls for 2 weeks: adjust volume/intensity split
3. If two or more recovery flags appear (sleep, soreness, output decline): deload 4-7 days
4. If injury warning signs appear: reduce intensity immediately and shift to maintainable work

## Success Criteria At Year End

The year is successful when the following are true:

1. Dunk ability achieved or dunk make-rate is clearly established
2. Side split at or near floor with control
3. Lean state reached and maintained without major performance loss
4. D1-aligned strength outputs maintained/improved
5. Clean & Jerk at 100 kg (or within final peak range with clear runway)

## Guiding Principle

Consistency beats novelty.
We prioritize repeatable structure, clear metrics, and controlled tradeoffs over constantly changing programs.
